# Skill: Adding a filter (backend + frontend)

Use when adding a new filter to any list — products, categories, orders, etc.

## Decision: backend filter vs frontend filter

```
Dataset is large (products, orders) → filter in BACKEND (never bring all rows to filter client-side)
Dataset is small (≤50 rows, e.g. categories) → frontend filter is acceptable
Filter needs DB data (stock count, join) → MUST be backend
Filter is UI-only (grid size, collapsed section) → frontend only, never involves API
```

When in doubt: **backend first**.

---

## Backend filter — full pattern

### Step 1 — Add the filter to `filters.py`

```python
# apps/{app}/filters.py
import django_filters
from django.db.models import Exists, OuterRef, Q
from apps.{app}.models import {Model}, {RelatedModel}


class {Model}Filter(django_filters.FilterSet):
    # Simple field filter
    is_featured = django_filters.BooleanFilter(field_name="is_featured")

    # Custom method filter (use when logic can't map to a single field)
    on_sale = django_filters.BooleanFilter(method="filter_on_sale")
    out_of_stock = django_filters.BooleanFilter(method="filter_out_of_stock")

    class Meta:
        model = {Model}
        fields = [
            "is_featured",
            "on_sale",
            "out_of_stock",
        ]

    def filter_on_sale(self, queryset, name, value):
        """Products with compare_at_price set (active sale price)."""
        del name
        if value is None:
            return queryset
        if value:
            return queryset.filter(compare_at_price__isnull=False)
        return queryset.filter(compare_at_price__isnull=True)

    def filter_out_of_stock(self, queryset, name, value):
        """Products with no active variant that has stock > 0."""
        del name
        if value is None:
            return queryset
        has_stock = {RelatedModel}.objects.filter(
            product_id=OuterRef("pk"),
            is_active=True,
            stock__gt=0,
        )
        if value:
            return queryset.filter(~Exists(has_stock))
        return queryset.filter(Exists(has_stock))
```

### Step 2 — Verify FilterSet is registered on the ViewSet

```python
# apps/{app}/views.py
class {Model}ViewSet(viewsets.ModelViewSet):
    filter_backends = [DjangoFilterBackend, filters.SearchFilter, filters.OrderingFilter]
    filterset_class = {Model}Filter  # ← must be set
```

### Step 3 — Test the filter manually

```bash
# Verify the filter works before writing frontend code
curl "http://localhost:8000/api/v1/{endpoint}/?on_sale=true"
curl "http://localhost:8000/api/v1/{endpoint}/?out_of_stock=true"
```

